description.text:
You can use these parts to make a removable front enclosure/window for an Ultimaker and other printers too. This is useful if you don't need a door on all the time, or don't want to make any permanent modifications. Also it looks better. It simply snaps on the front with magnetic force.

Features:
-Non-permanent, completely removable door and fixtures.
-Fully magnetic
-No glue required
-Will not affect or interfere with any top enclosure

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.15mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Hinge needs supports below screw holes.

MATERIALS

Panel: .093in (2.4mm) thick Lexan (thinner=OK)
Screws: 6mm long machine screws in M2.5 or M3, or (similar diameter=OK)
Magnets: 12mm x 3mm Neodymium (other sizes less than 12mm width=OK)

and:
-Painter's tape, or superglue if desired, to hold magnets on the interior frame.
-Drill, and small drill bits to drill holes for screws in your Panel

IMPORTANT: There are two types of magnetic hinge.

One version is "open" faced to fit many size of magnet.

The other one, pictured, is designed to seal the 12mm x 3mm (or smaller) magnet inside DURING THE PRINT.

If you want to use the sealed version, FIRST MAKE SURE THAT THE EXTRUDER HEAD IS NOT MAGNETIC!!!!!! Then inspect the layers in your slicer to familiarize yourself with when the pocket is sealed. It happens about 50% through the print. Note that there is a small cosmetic groove made in the layer just before the top is sealed. While printing, watch for your extruder to make the motion of this groove to alert you that it is about to perform the sealing. Then pause the print and insert your magnet. If you don't feel comfortable doing this or want to use a larger magnet, just use the open version. I am not liable for any damages or injuries by attempting this method.

INSTRUCTIONS

1) Print out at least four magnet hinges. Add more as needed depending on weight of panel and strength of your magnets.

2) Mark and drill the screw holes in your panel for the hinges. Use your hinges as a guide for the drill bit too.

3) Install hinges and tape the panel to the front of the enclosure with the alignment you want.

4) Place magnets on the interior wall of your printer and secure them with tape or glue. Don't put them in a place where they interfere with the extruder rails or other magnetic parts of the printer.

5) Install the handle if you want.

6) +Bonus, for people with Ultimaker:

You can conveniently rest this lid on the front of the case by backing out the top two case screws very slightly.

To do this, print two of the "washers" and insert them into the two M3 screws in the top of the front face panel. Now those screws will extend out of the panel by enough to rest your enclosure panel on. Now just drill out two matching holes in your enclosure panel to fit. Now when you place your panel, it should rest perfectly in the notch on top of these screws.

Edit 6/30/2017: My new stencil holder will make you smile (and be more organized):

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2412238

In the immortal words of Bill Lumbergh from Office Space:

Oh, and remember: next Friday... is Hawaiian shirt day. So, you know, if you want to, go ahead and wear a Hawaiian shirt and jeans.

I know that a simple coffee stencil won't make every day feel like Friday, but maybe it can improve your mood a little, or the mood of others?

In fact, it's been scientifically proven that giving feels better than receiving neurologically!

If you need something else to smile about, here's a picture of my wife rescuing a baby bird:

https://www.flickr.com/photos/theamarand/17402580262/

So the first thing you do, is download this stencil, and then print it out. Hopefully, you have a mug or cup that this will fit over. Just the expectation of having a fun stencil to print will actually cause a positive effect on your brain, it's true! Think about how much fun it will be to level your printer (okay, maybe not that) - and press the print button, watching your plastic print monkey draw layer, by layer, as you drift into a deeper and deeper sle....

Wait, no! Don't fall asleep! Wake up! It's Friday!

Or at least, it's Friday right now, when I'm posting this. I saved the smiley face coffee stencil for posting on Friday because, although Monday probably needs a smile more than Friday, I think people are more perky and receptive on Friday, unless they work a weird weekly shift where the weekdays are the weekend, or you work every day of the week or something, and that sucks.

But seriously...download this coffee stencil, or peruse my other coffee stencils too - you could start a collection! (Don't forget to share pictures/makes.)

Before I forget, here are direct links to my other stencils:

Heart: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2393694
Five-Pointed Star: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2395326
Five-Petal Flower: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2396760

Print it out, marvel in its simplicity, and then make yourself a cup of coffee. Shake up your creamer, pour it on top, and then put the stencil over the top. Then, pick your powder: cinnamon, cocoa, powdered sugar, whatever - and put it into a little sieve. I find that my little baby metal mesh tea ball works great (see photos), but whatever works for you. Just remember, you want to dust the powder over the top of the stencil, not dump it....

Make yourself a cup of coffee, and that will give you energy! Then you can make another cup of coffee for a friend, lover, or even a co-worker, or enemy. Even enemies like coffee. And with this smiley face, you're sure to get a smile or a laugh out of anyone you give this to, unless they're a real jerk. In which case, you can't please everyone, can you?

But yes, it's Friday, and here in smiley face coffee stencil world, it's always Friday! And you can come back and look at the smiley face stencil here on Thingiverse if you're feeling down, and just need something happy to look at. But it's way more fun to print your own, and have one that you can hold in your hands, maybe let your dog or cat sniff it? They like peanut butter. Toss it like a toy. Who knows?

If you have an idea for a custom stencil, please let me know! I can also make any or all of my stencils in a different size fairly easily. Just need your required diameter, and if you need a taller or shorter "lip" than what I've provided. It probably makes sense to print one of these and try it out on your container first, and if it's too big, too small, just measure the outside diameter (and maybe the inside diameter too, so I can appropriately place the stencil), and post a comment, or even better, create an I Made One entry, and share pictures there. It helps me keep track of the little custom projects I'm working on.

Right now, I'm working on several ideas: dog paw, cat paw, dog bone.... So if there's a symbol/shape you really like, please let me know!

Notes:

This guy is super solid. Sometimes, with stencils, you have to put in support pieces. You want the support pieces to be small enough to not really show up that much, but strong enough that they won't just break off. Durability versus aesthetics. Fun stuff. But in this case, it's just three holes, and it should print just fine. No supports or rafts required.

How to Use

Using a coffee stencil is fairly simple:

1) Put coffee in vessel
2) Shake up your creamer a lot, so it's bubbly
3) Pour creamer over coffee slowly, so it stays at the top
4) Leave very little "headroom" at the top - maybe 1/4" or less?
5) Place stencil over the top of the vessel
6) Lightly sprinkle the powder of your choice over the top of the stencil

I like to make sure I sprinkle over the entire stencil, that way I know I'm getting into all the nooks and crannies.

Here's a video if you're more of a visual learner:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M8ugnBwyCgk

Fusion 360 and Simplify3D

I have a "clean" version of the stencil that has nothing cut out, so after I designed the first stencil, now I just put new SVG files in and cut through the plastic. Super easy. It takes time to make sure I cut out the right parts, or put supports in where (and when) needed, but I like the fact that I can just keep making new stencils.

I love the way Fusion 360 works, and keeps improving. It does a great job of rendering mockups so I can take a look at items before I print them.

Simplify3D does a great job of slicing, giving me metrics (time, filament, cost estimate), and it makes good prints.

The 5pin binder connections are available from the likes of RS, I epoxied a new one into the new back to ensure it's still rain proof, the original rubber seal still fits this.

I disconnected the charger wire from the external connector as I'll be charging these on a bench charger and just replacing the battery when it gets low.

comments.text:
Apparently Simplify3D deals with Blender exported stl's differently than Cura, which is what I usually use. I have had the complaint on a few of my designs that they are not scaled. So I did some investigating and experimenting wit the program, and apparently you need to set the scale factor to 1000 when exporting out of blender so the dimensions to come out right in Simplify3D.
So sorry for the trouble everyone. Lesson learned. From now on all my designs will feature the 2 different scales depending on the slicer you use, and I am going to update all my old models.
Cheers!

description.text:
To use:

  1. Print the template.
  2. (Optional) For best results, sand the sides smooth to get rid of layer lines.
  3. Adhere template to the paper backing on the vinyl. I use a gluestick for this.
  4. Cut around the template, and in the holes, with a razor, craft knife, exacto blade, etc.
  5. (Optional) For best results, use a 5mm hole punch on the up/down buttons for easy, perfect circles. You can also use the 5mm hole punch for the rounded screen edges and a 3mm hole punch for the edges on the menu button and vent holes.
  6. Cut an extra piece of the plain rectangle. (The one with no holes)
  7. Peel the vinyl off the template and adhere it to the mod. Depending on the adhesive you used to adhere the template to the paper backing, you should be able to peel the backing off the template pretty easily.

The plain rectangle pieces will cover your battery doors. The other two pieces should be obvious; one is the front where your screen and buttons are, the other is the back where the vent holes are.

description.text:
A quick test for testing the XY scale of your printer. The model prints in under 10 minutes and features a 20x20x20 frame which you can measure to verify and fine tune the scale of the models both inside and out. Here are some useful things to know:

  • The model is 20x20x20 mm in size on the outside, 15.2x15.2x15.2 mm on the inside and every frame is 2.4 mm in width. Use these measurements to verify your printer's precision. Please take a look at the third image for measurements.
  • There is a little dent on the bottom of the model in one corner. The dent lets you easily pry the model off the bed, but also tells you the orientation. It is located pointing towards negative X and Y. Please refer to the third image on this upload for a better visualisation.
  • For fastest printing, print this with walls being 1.2 mm in width or more. This will ensure that the printer prints out the model using straight lines instead of infill.
  • The model uses curved corners to further speed up printing, but also to minimize the possibility of overshooting sharp corners interfering with the measurement.

I have also included the Blender file in case you want to edit it further.

HOW TO CALIBRATE:

You will first need to know your current motor steps per mm. You can find this value in your firmware or in your printer's settings somewhere. Let's call this value Old Steps. Once you have this, print this model out. To calibrate one of the axes, for example the X axis here, you will need to measure the following two values:

  • The X width of the whole model. This value will be around 20 mm. Let's call this value Measured Width.
  • The X width of one of the frames. This value should be around 2.4 mm, but expect a larger value due to the squished in layers. Let's call this value Measured Frame.

Once you have these values, enter them into the following formula (don't change the value 17.6, it is a constant):

New Steps = Old Steps * (17.6 / (Measured Width - Measured Frame))

Now you can use the New Steps value for your calibrated motor steps! Use this formula for calculating both X and Y separately. Calculating the steps like this should give you the correct inner and outer diameters on all of your models! Keep in mind that the outer and inner diameters will always be a bit wider and a bit thinner respectively because of the layer squish. This is normal and can be minimized by a smaller nozzle.

This is a drag chain that is compatible with the LPA X-Carriage Mod. It raises the chain a tad, So you may lose a little bit of Z axis on top, but it works fine. :)

Note: Yours will probably turn out better than mine, because I didn't post-process the chain links like I should have, so mine are a bit sticky sometimes. If I took them off and sanded them, they wouldn't stick.

comments.text: The part that attaches to the LPA carriage is the hardest part. Use supports both outside and inside, most likely with a raft, or at least a large brim. You might also be able to turn it 90 degrees right, so the largest flat part is facing down, but it'll still have to use support to build up to the flat area.

This is a set of 4 caps for the tops of the 8mm threaded rods which control the Z-axis for the makerbot.  I have been lugging my makerbot around in my car almost every day, and got a few scratches on the glove compartment from the rough metal rod ends.  I drafted these caps in OpenSCAD, mostly to learn how to use the CSG modeling.  It's a very simple part, but it's saved me any more auto interior damage.
Each cap is a cylinder with a cone segment subtracted from it.  On my 'bot they screw on fairly tight and can be used to twist the z-axis up and down.  The parts are parametric, but you probably don't need it unless you want to use it to make end caps for a different size threaded rod.

Open endcaps.scad in OpenSCAD
Design -> Compile and Render
Design -> Export to STL
Skeinforge
Print
Cut away the ooze and raft. If you want nicer looking endcaps, print the caps one at a time by commenting out the last 4 lines of endcaps.scad, and replace with "endcap();", then follow the above. Printing one at a time eliminates some of the irregularity and oozing.

description.text: This is a remix of the "eye" portion of CONCENTRIX's super-awesome HAL 9000 Prop Replica. The eye has been modified to use a "cheap" ($35) 37MM screw mount fish eye lens. The specific lens that I used was the "Neewer 37MM 0.3X HD Ultra Fisheye Lens for Sony DCR Cameras..." which can be found here: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0049S6VHU, but I'd imagine that any of the other identical looking fish eye lenses would work.

For assembly, remove the lens hood (held onto the lens with a few small set screws) from the lens, and then press into the HAL_Eye_Housing. Mine is simply friction fit, but you could add a small amount of hot glue to the back of the lip that the lens hood was sitting on top of before pressing it into the housing.

The HAL_Eye_LED piece is held in place using the len's rear screw-on lens cover. The center of the cover was cut out to allow the HAL_Eye_LED piece to protrude/allow the wires through.

Topographical map of Bergen, Norway.
That web page helped me a lot:) http://www.navimationresearch.net/tag/heightmap/

Data source

The height map of Bergen with 10 m resolution was downloaded from http://data.kartverket.no/download/.

Data conversion

*.dem file from kartverket was converted using GDAL software to PNG format. The PNG file contained different shades of gray, corresponding to different heights. The following command was used for conversion:

gdal_translate -scale 0 700 -of PNG *.dem heightmap.png

where scale sets 0 meters height to black and 700 meters height to white.

Building of the mdel

The 3D model was built with OpenSCAD using the surface() function. The function transforms PNG file to a 3D profile.

Conjunto de 3 piezas que sirven para colgar objetos relativos al ámbito de la música.
Cuenta con 2 piezas principales, la cuales una es abierta y otra cerrada, y 1 pieza de terminación.
La pieza de terminación, encastra por tolerancia dimensional mediante 2 torretas en 2 cavidades que hay en la pieza abierta.
Todas las piezas fueron pensadas para ser impresas en 3d, y a pesar de su compleja morfología todas tienen una superfice plana, que sirve de apoyo al momento de imprimirlas.
También fueron diseñadas para poder ser impresas en una impresora que tenga un plato de 20x20 cms.
Respecto a las dimensiones propias de las piezas, la pieza abierta, que es la de mayor tamaño, fue diseñada sus medidas externas e internas, en función de que pueda contener cajas de cds, como contener y soportar libros de tamaño A4.
La pieza abierta, sus dimensiones fueron diseñadas en función de sostener distintas guitarras a través de la sección del mástil, como así, también sostener y exhibir auriculares y su correspondiente cable(tanto para guitarra o auricular).
En el caso de la pieza abierta, sus dimensiones y diseño permiten colocar el soporte paralelo al piso como rotado hasta 45º en ambos sentidos, sin perder la funcionalidad y logrando distintas formas de sostener los objetos.

Si bien la funcionalidad de las piezas tienen como fin objetos concretos, a traves de geometrías simples y formas puras, se buscó resolver las necesidades de soporte de éstos, como así generar soportes de formas "genéricas", pudiendo asi ser funcionales a otros objetos.
Es así, seiguiendo una lógica simple, que si el soporte funciona para un formato A4, y se necesita el objeto para otro formato, el mismo es factible de ser descargado, modificado y vuelto a subir para imprimir y resolver la necesidad del nuevo formato.

Por eso decidí disolver los productos en 2 tipos, en abierto y cerrado, dado que responden necesidades diferentes, ya que el tema de variar los tamaños se puede incluso cambiar desde la impresión sin volver a diseñarlo.

Las 2 piezas pueden ser amuradas a una pared, mediante un tornillo de 3.5x50 y segun la carga que vaya a soportar, se pueden usar tarugos Nª5-Nº6-Nº8.

ORIGEN

El proyecto es resultado de una propuesta universitaria, donde era necesario realizar producto de impresión3d que contara con 3 piezas.
Durante el diseño de las piezas, se imprimió un prototipo(foto) en PLA, para poder probar su funcionalidad como sus dimensiones y resistencia a los esfuerzos.

Todas las piezas fueron modelas en Rhinoceros.

Ever wondered what the antibodies that help protect you from infection look like? This is a model of one type (class) of antibody, called IgG (immunoglobulin G) It's a symmetrical structure consisting of two "heavy" chains, which give the Y shape in the model, and two additional chains, the "light" chains, which are associated with each of the arms of the Y. This model is derived from an x-ray crystallographic structure of IgG1, which is available from the protein databank (PDB). The nominal molecular surface of the IgG has been skinned, so all the various individual molecules get fused into a continuous surface. Unless my quick calculation is off, the model, if left as is, is approximately 6.2 million times bigger than an actual IgG.
The two identical arms (each being partly made of a heavy chain and a light chain, bind to the antibodies target "antigen" - so a single IgG can bind to two identical target molecules. Search for antibody on the web, if you are curious about the detail!

Needs complete support, get it as flat as possible to the build surface, so have a good look before  generating the code.  I'll try making it as two colour next time, so heavy and light chains show  themselves.

author: STARBOUIF

description.text:
Organizers for the board game Lords of Vegas, and the Up! expansion.

This is a collection of 4 tray designs to hold all the components of the game. I designed them with ease of printing and functionality in mind. All the parts are meant to be printed flat, they require no supports, will fit on a 120mm x, 120mm, x120mm, bed and should require minimal to no post print clean up. They not only function as storage, but can be used during play. Also included are lids for all trays for those who travel with your games.

A general note, manufacturing and print runs may change the size of the game pieces. Plus your printer is not my printer. Test and adjust accordingly.

Here is a rundown of parts, and notes on each:

-= Card Holder =-

Print: 1

This was sized for cards sleeved in Ultra Pro sleeves. If you are going far enough to print organizers, I'm assuming you are also protecting your cards... If not it's easy enough to scale for un-sleeved, or even different sleeves. That said, this is barely tall enough for all the card if you include the action/player/house cards. I highly recommend printing the lid, or scaling the Z up a bit to prevent them slipping out in storage.

-= Tile Holder =-

Print: 5 (Base Game) + 4 (Up!)

These are for the casino tiles, and as uploaded, hold 12 tiles. You'll need one for each color, and if you have the expansion four more. I put the "spare" tiles for each color at the bottom.

-= Money Tray =-

Print: 2

Each one holds 2 denominations, and are deep enough to accommodate the extra money that comes with the expansion. If you are printing on a MPSM and having problems getting this to slice in Cura, disable your skirt, or just reduce it's distance from the model.

-= Player Tray =-

Print: 4 (Base Game) + 2 (Up!)

These are designed to hold all 12 dice, 10 markers, and the scoring chip for each player. simplifies setup immensely.
